{{orphan|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox Court Case | name = Vickery v Waitaki International Ltd | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 5 November 1991 | full name = Vickery v Waitaki International Ltd | citations = [1992] 2 NZLR 58 | judges = [[Robin Brunskill Cooke|Cooke P]], [[Ivor Richardson|Richardson J]], [[Thomas Munro Gault|Gault]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | Keywords = }}
Vickery v Waitaki International Ltd [1992] 2 NZLR 58 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding terms implied by the Courts to give "business efficacy" to a contract that would have otherwise been unworkable.<ref name="Chetwin, Graw, Tiong">{{cite book |title=An introduction to the Law of Contract in New Zealand |edition=4th |last1=Chetwin |first1=Maree |last2=Graw |first2=Stephen |last3=Tiong |first3=Raymond |publisher=Thomson Brookers |ISBN=0-86472-555-8 |year=2006 |page={{page needed|date=January 2014}}}}</ref>
